Title: Privilege Escalation: Lower Privilege User Can Disable MFA via Super Admin URL
Description: A lower privilege user can access and exploit a Super Admin feature to disable MFA during login. By directly updating the value in the Super Admin URL (intended for high-privilege users), the lower privilege user is able to disable MFA, even while they are still on the MFA setup page. This vulnerability allows the user to bypass security measures meant to enforce MFA, thus compromising the authentication process and exposing the application to unauthorized access.

Impact:

Users with lower privileges can perform high-privilege actions, such as disabling MFA.
This can lead to unauthorized access, account compromise, and security breaches.
Recommendation:

Implement strict access control on URLs and features to ensure that only authorized users (Super Admins) can access sensitive functions.
Validate user permissions on the server side before executing any action related to MFA settings.
Regularly audit access control rules to ensure that privilege separation is correctly enforced.
